# Gogo HTTP, Admin, API, And Auth Rules

Use this rule when adding routes, middleware, views, admin screens, APIs, auth,
sessions, groups, permissions, or access checks.

Framework module: `github.com/cybersaksham/gogo`.

## HTTP

- Put root URL wiring in `{{.ProjectName}}/urls.go`.
- Put app routes and handlers in each app's `urls.go`.
- Use Gogo HTTP request/response helpers, route patterns, URL reversing,
  middleware, decorators, redirects, generic views, and error handling.
- Keep middleware order explicit in project settings or middleware wiring.

## Admin

- Register admin entries in app `admin.go` files or project admin wiring.
- Configure list display, search, filters, readonly fields, inlines, widgets,
  actions, autocomplete, delete behavior, and history intentionally.
- Gate admin access through staff/superuser and permission checks.
- Keep admin actions auditable and avoid destructive bulk actions without
  confirmation or explicit permission checks.

## API

- Use Gogo API serializers, model serializers, views, viewsets, routers,
  parsers, renderers, authentication, permissions, pagination, filtering,
  throttling, uploads, metadata, versioning, validation, and OpenAPI helpers.
- Keep serializers responsible for transport validation and conversion.
- Keep business rules in services so admin, HTTP, API, and tasks share behavior.
- Return consistent API errors through Gogo API response/error helpers.

## Auth, Sessions, And Permissions

- Use the built-in Gogo auth toolkit for users, groups, permissions, password
  hashing, forms, tokens, middleware, decorators, and content types.
- Extend/inherit from the built-in auth models rather than replacing the auth
  system unless a future Gogo version explicitly supports configurable auth.
- Store authorization rules in permission constants/helpers and reuse them in
  admin, API, HTTP views, and tasks.
- Keep session and CSRF settings secure in production.
